    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## Create Dataloaders\n",
        "Now we are going to do 3 things:\n",
        "\n",
        "1.   Letâ€™s preprocess our data using the compose method, which is a simple method to apply multiple preprocessing functions like normalization and data augmentation to our dataset.\n",
        "\n",
        "2.   Letâ€™s use ImageFolder to create a pytorch dataset. PyTorch infers the class automatically if the subdirectories structure is well defined (as in our case).\n",
        "\n",
        "3.   Use the DataLoader to slice our data in batches."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Yy8497xnOxlj"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "traindir = \"/content/data/training\"\n",
        "validation_dir = \"/content/data/validation\"\n",
        "\n",
        "#transformations\n",
        "train_transforms = transforms.Compose([transforms.Resize((224,224)),\n",
        "                                       transforms.ToTensor(),\n",
        "                                       torchvision.transforms.Normalize(\n",
        "                                           mean=[0.485, 0.456, 0.406],\n",
        "                                           std=[0.229, 0.224, 0.225],\n",
        "    ),\n",
        "                                       ])\n",
        "test_transforms = transforms.Compose([transforms.Resize((224,224)),\n",
        "                                      transforms.ToTensor(),\n",
        "                                      torchvision.transforms.Normalize(\n",
        "                                          mean=[0.485, 0.456, 0.406],\n",
        "                                          std=[0.229, 0.224, 0.225],\n",
        "    ),\n",
        "                                      ])\n",
        "\n",
        "#datasets\n",
        "train_data = datasets.ImageFolder(traindir,transform=train_transforms)\n",
        "validation_data = datasets.ImageFolder(validation_dir,transform=test_transforms)\n",
        "\n",
        "#dataloader\n",
        "trainloader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(train_data, shuffle = True, batch_size=16)\n",
        "validation_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(validation_data, shuffle = True, batch_size=16)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "GaDbYv-7RUlQ"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Create class for testing unlabeled images\n",
        "class UnlabeledImageFolder(DatasetFolder):\n",
        "    def __init__(self, root, transform=None, target_transform=None,\n",
        "                 loader=default_loader, is_valid_file=None):\n",
        "        super(UnlabeledImageFolder, self).__init__(root, loader, IMG_EXTENSIONS if is_valid_file is None else None,\n",
        "                                                   transform=transform,\n",
        "                                                   target_transform=target_transform,\n",
        "                                                   is_valid_file=is_valid_file)\n",
        "        self.imgs = self.samples"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "5Qgi_AQMWsxW"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "test_dir = \"/content/data/test\"\n",
        "test_data = UnlabeledImageFolder(test_dir, transform=test_transforms)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "q0wb9I_sWwQQ"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## Training step function\n",
        "The training step is always defined by 3 things: model, optimizer and loss function. So letâ€™s write a function that returns a train step function given in input these 3 entities. In this way, we donâ€™t have to rewrite the same code again and again!"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "OZMuZOlRPC3q"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "def make_train_step(model, optimizer, loss_fn):\n",
        "  def train_step(x,y):\n",
        "    #make prediction\n",
        "    yhat = model(x)\n",
        "    #enter train mode\n",
        "    model.train()\n",
        "    #compute loss\n",
        "    loss = loss_fn(yhat,y)\n",
        "\n",
        "    loss.backward()\n",
        "    optimizer.step()\n",
        "    optimizer.zero_grad()\n",
        "    #optimizer.cleargrads()\n",
        "\n",
        "    return loss\n",
        "  return train_step"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "-1abudkbRfSz"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## Build the model\n",
        "In solving most Kaggle tasks you donâ€™t write a network from scratch but you use a pre-trained model called base_model and adapt it to the task at hand. Think of base_model as a model that has already learned to recognize important features in images. What we want to do is to adapt it by adding a head composed of other dense layers. In our case, the last dense layer will be composed of a single neuron that will use a sigmoid activation function so that we will have an output probability of being 0 or 1 (cat or dog).#\n",
        "\n",
        "![image.png](data:image/png;base64,)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "HfYIAvNJPIok"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "We must be careful not to train the base model that has already been previously trained.\n",
        "\n",
        "Letâ€™s download a pretrained model (resnet) and freeze all the parameters. Then we are going to change the last linear layer in order to customize the model to become a binary classifier. Rember model and data must be on the same device (GPU)."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "JH2hUPx0PbNH"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "device = \"cuda\" if torch.cuda.is_available() else \"cpu\"\n",
        "print(\"Using \" + device + \" device\")\n",
        "\n",
        "model = models.resnet18(pretrained=True)\n",
        "\n",
        "#freeze all params (prevent modifying the pretrained network)\n",
        "for params in model.parameters():\n",
        "  params.requires_grad_ = False\n",
        "\n",
        "#add a new final layer\n",
        "nr_filters = model.fc.in_features  #number of input features of last layer\n",
        "model.fc = nn.Linear(nr_filters, 1)\n",
        "\n",
        "model = model.to(device)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "iUILvQdvRiJq",
        "outputId": "b4fb8e1c-493f-4a15-f1f5-9d7186fe448e"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "Using cuda device\n"
          ]
        },

          "name": "stderr",
          "text": [

            "  warnings.warn(\n",
            "/usr/local/lib/python3.10/dist-packages/torchvision/models/_utils.py:223: UserWarning: Arguments other than a weight enum or `None` for 'weights' are deprecated since 0.13 and may be removed in the future. The current behavior is equivalent to passing `weights=ResNet18_Weights.IMAGENET1K_V1`. You can also use `weights=ResNet18_Weights.DEFAULT` to get the most up-to-date weights.\n",
            "  warnings.warn(msg)\n"
          ]
        }

    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Here's a brief excerpt of some of the 1000 classes found in ResNet-18:\n",
        "\n",
        "*  Tench\n",
        "*  Goldfish\n",
        "*  Great white shark\n",

      ],

      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "We now need to define loss, optimizer and train_step.\n",
        "\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Cn_1R-m-PePs"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "#loss\n",
        "loss_fn = BCEWithLogitsLoss() #binary cross entropy with sigmoid, so no need to use sigmoid in the model\n",
        "\n",
        "#optimizer\n",
        "optimizer = torch.optim.Adam(model.fc.parameters())\n",
        "\n",
        "#train step\n",
        "train_step = make_train_step(model, optimizer, loss_fn)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "mg_qyRHURo_f"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## Train the model\n",
        "Letâ€™s write our training and evaluation phase. We are going to also implement Early Stopping and save at each epoch the best model."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "9xfDH-GkPgb8"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "losses = []\n",
        "val_losses = []\n",
        "\n",
        "epoch_train_losses = []\n",
        "epoch_test_losses = []\n",
        "\n",
        "n_epochs = 10\n",
        "early_stopping_tolerance = 2\n",
        "early_stopping_threshold = 0.03\n",
        "early_stopping_counter = 0\n",
        "\n",
        "for epoch in range(n_epochs):\n",
        "  epoch_loss = 0\n",
        "  for index, data in tqdm(enumerate(trainloader), total = len(trainloader), desc = \"Training\"): #iterate ove batches\n",
        "    x_batch, y_batch = data\n",
        "    x_batch = x_batch.to(device) #move to gpu\n",
        "    y_batch = y_batch.unsqueeze(1).float() #convert target to same nn output shape\n",
        "    y_batch = y_batch.to(device) #move to gpu\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "    loss = train_step(x_batch, y_batch)\n",
        "    epoch_loss += loss/len(trainloader)\n",
        "    losses.append(loss)\n",
        "\n",
        "  epoch_train_losses.append(epoch_loss)\n",
        "  print('\\nEpoch : {}, train loss : {}'.format(epoch+1,epoch_loss))\n",
        "\n",
        "  #validation doesnt requires gradient\n",
        "  with torch.no_grad():\n",
        "    cum_loss = 0\n",
        "    for index, data in tqdm(enumerate(validation_loader), total = len(validation_loader), desc = \"Validating\"):\n",
        "      x_batch, y_batch = data\n",
        "      x_batch = x_batch.to(device)\n",
        "      y_batch = y_batch.unsqueeze(1).float() #convert target to same nn output shape\n",
        "      y_batch = y_batch.to(device)\n",
        "\n",
        "      #model to eval mode\n",
        "      model.eval()\n",
        "\n",
        "      yhat = model(x_batch)\n",
        "      val_loss = loss_fn(yhat,y_batch)\n",
        "      cum_loss += loss/len(validation_loader)\n",
        "      val_losses.append(val_loss.item())\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "    epoch_test_losses.append(cum_loss)\n",
        "    print('Epoch : {}, val loss : {}'.format(epoch+1,cum_loss))\n",
        "\n",
        "    best_loss = min(epoch_test_losses)\n",
        "\n",
        "    #save best model\n",
        "    if cum_loss <= best_loss:\n",
        "      best_model_wts = model.state_dict()\n",
        "\n",
        "    #early stopping\n",
        "    if cum_loss > best_loss:\n",
        "      early_stopping_counter +=1\n",
        "\n",
        "    if (early_stopping_counter == early_stopping_tolerance) or (best_loss <= early_stopping_threshold):\n",
        "      print(\"/nTerminating: early stopping\")\n",
        "      break #terminate training\n",
        "\n",
        "#load best model\n",
        "model.load_state_dict(best_model_wts)"
      ],

        "Test the accuracy of the model on validation data"

      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "def test_accuracy(model, validation_data):\n",
        "    model.eval()  # Set the model to evaluation mode\n",
        "    correct = 0   # Initialize count of correct predictions\n",
        "\n",
        "    with torch.no_grad():  # Disable gradient computation during testing\n",
        "        for images, labels in tqdm(validation_data, desc=\"Testing\"):\n",
        "            images = images.to(device)\n",
        "\n",
        "            # Ensure the images tensor is 4D (batch, channels, height, width)\n",
        "            if len(images.shape) == 3:\n",
        "                images = images.unsqueeze(0)  # Add batch dimension\n",
        "\n",
        "            # Convert integer labels to tensors and move to the device\n",
        "            labels = torch.tensor([labels], dtype=torch.float32).to(device)\n",
        "\n",
        "            outputs = torch.sigmoid(model(images))\n",
        "            predicted = (outputs > 0.5).float()  # Convert predictions to 0 or 1\n",
        "\n",
        "            correct += (predicted.squeeze() == labels).sum().item()\n",
        "\n",
        "    # Calculate accuracy using direct len(validation_data)\n",
        "    accuracy = 100 * correct / len(validation_data)\n",
        "\n",
        "    return accuracy\n",
        "\n",
        "accuracy = test_accuracy(model, validation_data)\n",
        "print(\"\\n\")\n",
        "print(f\"Accuracy on test data: {accuracy:.2f}%\")\n"
      ],
